es, Valdáliga, Cantabria, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fernando","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A modern form of the old Spanish name <i>Ferdinando</i>, which is of Germanic (Visigothic) origin, from <i>farð</i> ‘journey’ (or possibly an altered form of <i>frið</i> ‘peace’) + <i>nand</i> ‘ready, prepared’. The name was hereditary in the royal families of Spain from an early date. It was borne by  Ferdinand I  (  d. 1065 ) of Castile and Leon, who conducted successful campaigns against the Moors, and by his descendant  Ferdinand V  (  1452–1516 ), who finally expelled the Moors from Spain altogether; he also gave financial backing to Columbus. Through the marriage in  1496  of his daughter  Joan the Mad of Castile  to the Habsburg  Archduke Philip , the name Ferdinand also became hereditary in the Austrian imperial family. Their younger son, Ferdinand (  1503–64 ), acquired the succession to the kingdoms of Hungary and Bohemia by marriage in  1521 , and became Holy Roman Emperor in  1558 .  See  <b>Ferdinand</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fernán","meanings":["A modern form of the old Spanish name <i>Ferdinando</i>, which is 